<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUN 92 / Parliament and Politics: GMB poll cheer for Labour
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE UNIONS have re-established their credibility as representatives of
Labour voters, according to the GMB general workers' union after analysis of
polling around the April general election.
Figures supplied to the union by the Mori polling organisation showed that
Labour took a 15 per cent lead over the Tories among trade unionists in a
25,000 sample. Labour's share was 46 per cent against 31 per cent for the
Tories.
The statistics will be used by trade unions to rebut accusations that they
did not deliver Labour votes from among their members, and to defend links
with the party.
According to Mori, Labour's vote among trade unionists increased on 1987 by
4 per cent. The Liberal Democrats lost a similar percentage and the Tories
picked up 1 per cent.
It was the best result for Labour among trade unionists since 1979,
according to the analysis. However, a 'terrifying gender gap' was detected
among voters aged 18-24. Young male union members swung to Labour by 6.5 per
cent between 1987 and 1992 but support from young women members fell 14 per
cent.
Among all trade unionists there was a strong swing to Labour of 2.5 per cent
in the last three days of the election campaign, when other voters were
moving against Labour.
In the GMB's ballot for the Labour leadership, Mr John Smith - who is
sponsored by the union - polled 110,177 against Mr Bryan Gould's 30,267. For
the deputy leadership, Mrs Margaret Beckett polled 74,771 against Mr John
Prescott's 37,270 and Mr Gould's 28,158.
</TEXT>
