<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUN 92 / Parliament and Politics: Link to influential Senator
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN FRIEDMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ROBERT MAXWELL used former Senator John Tower, the influential Republican,
to seek US government assistance in 1988 for an aborted attempt to acquire
15 insolvent Texas savings-and-loans institutions, according to a former US
bank regulatory official.
Tower, who died in an air crash last year, was a paid consultant to Maxwell
and served on the board of Macmillan, the publisher owned by Maxwell
Communication Corporation (MCC).
In August 1988 Senator Tower went to see Mr Danny Wall, then chairman of the
Federal Home Loan Bank Board, the now-defunct agency that previously
regulated the US savings-and-loan industry.
The former Texan Senator met Mr Wall to argue on behalf of a bid by Maxwell
for a group of 15 failing savings-and-loan institutions that were later
declared inolvent, sold as a single package and renamed the Bluebonnet
Savings Bank.
According to documents obtained by the Financial Times, the Maxwell proposal
asked the Federal Savings and Loan Insurance Corporation to grant Maxwell 50
per cent of an estimated Dollars 86.3m of expected tax benefits.
A Congressional investigator claimed at the weekend that 'Maxwell hired
Tower to try and grease the savings-and-loan deal' because of his political
influence. Mr Wall, who resigned in March 1990, said he saw 'nothing
nefarious' in Tower's approach.
After leaving the Senate in 1985, Tower had a series of business ties to
Maxwell, for whom he acted as a paid consultant.
In April 1989 Tower was named by Maxwell to the board of directors of
Macmillan. Maxwell also paid the former senator to serve as chairman of two
Macmillan subsidiaries - Pergamon Brassey International Defence
Publications, a publisher, and the Armed Forces Journal, a monthly magazine.
Mr David Shaffer, the Macmillan chairman who was asked by a New York
bankruptcy court to manage MCC's US assets after MCC filed last December for
protection from creditors under US bankruptcy law, said Tower reported to
him 'and was a very important conduit to the defence industry who brought in
a lot of advertising'.
Mr Shaffer, who declined to say how much Tower was paid by Macmillan, noted
that Tower 'never attended any Macmillan board meetings while he was on the
board'.
</TEXT>
