FT  17 JUN 92 / Parliament and Politics: Clash over water pricing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN and IVOR OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE AVERAGE household water payment has increased by more than 47 per cent -
or three times the rate of inflation - since water companies were
privatised, Labour claimed yesterday, urging the government to give greater
priority to consumers' interests.
Ms Ann Taylor, shadow environment spokesman, attacked the government for
treating water as a marketable commodity rather than a 'vital natural
resource'.
The actual price increases compared with government predictions that water
prices would rise by between 7.5 and 12.5 per cent by the end of the
century, she said, opening an Opposition debate on water since
privatisation.
The Labour motion expressed alarm at the 'record profits, record dividends
and record salaries and perks of top management in the water companies',
especially at a time when households were facing record bills.
Mr David Maclean, environment minister, ruled out intervention to curb the
increased charges, and accused Labour of 'not having the nous to realise
that there is no investment without profits'.
Privatisation had overcome the handicap of severe under investment over 20
to 30 years, he said, praising the privatised companies for their Pounds
28bn investment programme. 'Transferring the water industry to the private
sector has given the industry the freedom to invest and to manage its
investment programme in the most efficient and economical way.'
Conservative anxiety about the rising charges was none the less underlined
when Mr Patrick Nicholls, the MP for Teignbridge, said they were set to
increase by well in excess of 15 per cent in the south-west over the next
five years and 'for the foreseeable future'.
A 'unique remedy' involving central funding might well be required, he
suggested.
</TEXT>
