<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUN 92 / Yeltsin predicts agreement on nuclear arms cuts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
RUSSIAN President Boris Yeltsin predicted yesterday that he and US President
George Bush would reach agreement on proposed radical reductions in
long-range nuclear arms during their two-day summit meeting in Washington.
'When the presidents take charge of something you can be sure it will be
handled in the most efficient way,' Mr Yeltsin told reporters before a
working lunch with Mr James Baker, secretary of state. 'That means we will
reach an agreement,' he said.
Mr Baker and Mr Andrei Kozyrev, the Russian foreign minister, have been
working in recent days on final details of a fresh arms accord aimed at cuts
in long-range missiles, bombers and submarines which go far beyond
reductions required under the Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty (Start).
Mr Bush yesterday welcomed Mr Yeltsin to the White House for 'a new kind of
summit: not a meeting between two powers struggling for global supremacy but
between two partners striving to build a democratic peace'.
Mr Yeltsin made it clear that in asking for US economic support he did not
wish to be treated as a supplicant.
'We have not come to ask your country to solve our problems for us. We have
brought along ideas and proposals,' he said.
'We have things to offer to the American farmer, to the American
industrialist and to the American banker.'
White House officials hope Mr Yeltsin's visit will give a boost to their
efforts to win congressional backing for a Russian aid bill, and Mr Bush
used his official welcoming speech to urge Congress to act on the bill.
Democratic leaders in Congress say, however, that the principal obstacle to
bringing the bill forward has been insufficient support from members of the
president's own Republican party.
But the issues set to dominate the agenda for the meeting between the two
leaders - nuclear disarmament, US aid to help smooth Russia's economic
transformation, trade and investment co-operation, - were initially
overshadowed yesterday by the possibility that some US prisoners of war
might still be alive in Russia.
Mr Yeltsin raised the possibility during his flight to Washington on Monday.
He struck a chord in the US, which remains committed to bringing the
physical remains of its war dead home. Opinion polls show an overwhelming
majority of the public believes that US servicemen listed as missing in
action during the Vietnam war are still held captive.
Mr Vyacheslav Kostikov, spokesman for Mr Yeltsin, said newly opened KGB
files showed a total of 2,800 Americans had been held in the Soviet Union
after the two world wars and the Korean and Vietnam conflicts.
'Many were interned, many were held in prisons. . . it is not excluded that
some might be still living,' he said.
Mr Yeltsin's motive in reopening the prisoner of war issue may be in part to
move beyond the political and economic issues on the summit agenda, and to
use his visit to kindle popular enthusiasm in the US for his reform
programme - and, in the process, for US financial aid.
</TEXT>
