<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JUN 92 / Money Markets: Cash expensive
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
SHORT RATES in the sterling cash market were firmer yesterday as dealers
took the whole day to remove the large shortage forecast by the Bank of
England.
As expected, the Bank forecast a shortage of Pounds 1bn at the start of what
is expected to be an expensive week for money. Many of the Bank's previous
repurchase agreements are due to expire this week. The shortage in
forthcoming days could add up to around Pounds 7bn.
To help remove yesterday's shortage, the Bank invited the discount houses to
tender bills in the early round. They also offered to purchase bills in the
longer dated Bands 3 and 4 at 9 21/32 per cent and 9 19/32 per cent
respectively.
At first, dealers waited to see whether the Bank would offer to buy these
bills at slightly lower rates: only Pounds 16m of Band-3 bank bills and
Pounds 29m of Band-4 bills were purchased. On top of this, Pounds 33m of
Band-1 bank bills and Pounds 74m of Band-2 bank bills were purchased at the
now established rate of 9 7/8 per cent.
As midday approached, dealers realised that the Bank would stick to these
dealing rates throughout the day. At the established rates, the Bank
purchased Pounds 70m of Band-1 treasury bills, Pounds 72m of Band-1 bank
bills, Pounds 20m of Band-2 bank bills, Pounds 237m of Band-3 bank bills,
Pounds 1m of Band-4 LA bills, and Pounds 161m of Band-4 bank bills. In the
afternoon, the shortage was revised to around Pounds 800m. The Bank bought
Pounds 37m of Band-1 bank bills and Pounds 13m of Band-2 bank bills. The
Bank also provided late assistance of around Pounds 70m.
The Bank was clearly not trying to signal a change in base rate policy by
dealing in longer-dated bills at these softer rates. Indeed, 3-month
sterling libor closed around 10 per cent. But one discount house dealer said
the Bank made life much easier by trading in Bands 3 and 4, which are long
dated, rather than alleviating the shortages with repurchase agreements that
would be expected to mature within a month. This way, the Bank pushes the
next cycle of shortages further out.
Period rates reflected the tone of trading. The overnight ended up at 10 3/4
per cent from 7 1/2 per cent on Friday night. The one-week rate finished at
10 5/16 per cent from 9 1/2 per cent, and the one-month rate at 10 1/16 per
cent from 9 15/16 per cent.
</TEXT>
