<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JUN 92 / Parliament and Politics: Conservatives rest on election
laurels
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AFTER two months of dispassionate analysis, the Tory party came to the
spectacular conclusion yesterday that its general election victory was 'a
ringing endorsement of its principles and policies', Ralph Atkins writes.
The official party version of events leading up to April 9 lays to rest any
suggestion that the Conservative victory might have been a lucky escape - or
even the product of Labour's shortcomings.
Campaign managers, who at the time faced a barrage of complaints about
lacklustre tactics and sweeping mid-campaign strategy, have been vindicated.
'I don't think there is any criticism in it,' said a party spokesman.
The Conservative research department, which compiled the paper, is prepared,
however, to offer lessons aplenty to Labour. Indeed its criticism of the
Opposition's 'damaging and discredited' economic policies and identity with
'narrow and shrinking' political interests dominates the report - from the
shadow Budget at the beginning of the campaign to Mr Neil Kinnock's
'ungracious speech' after the results.
'Labour's position is grave,' the report adds helpfully.
In contrast, Mr John Major has a 'winning style'.
When accused of perhaps a slight bias, Tory party officials confirmed the
report was but one of many campaign 'feed-back' studies prepared by senior
Tories. The others will not, however, be published.
</TEXT>
