<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JUN 92 / Parliament and Politics: Kinnock quits contest for European
job
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR NEIL KINNOCK, the Labour leader, last night withdrew from the contest for
the presidency of the European Communities' Confederation of Socialist
Parties because of a possible conflict with his party's stance on the
Maastricht treaty.
He withdrew after consultations in Lisbon with other socialists had pointed
to difficulties he would face if the confederation backed the treaty but
Labour chose to vote against it in the Commons.
The decision is another personal setback for Mr Kinnock, who is soon to
stand down as Labour leader. He is looking for a role in Labour politics
after his general election defeat, but felt obliged to withdraw from the
European confederation election even though there were no other candidates
for the post. He urged postponing the contest until the autumn.
Mr Kinnock said that, following the Danish referendum's rejection of the
Maastricht treaty, it was 'reasonable' for the Labour party to try to change
the treaty.
'This might involve the Labour party in delaying or opposing the Tory
version of the Maastricht Treaty,' he said in Lisbon.
'The possibility that Labour might oppose the Tory version of the treaty
could mean an inconsistency between my duties as president of the
confederation and my duties as leader of the Labour party and subsequently
as a Labour MP.'
</TEXT>
