<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JUN 92 / Parliament and Politics: Labour party 'dream ticket' rises
in value
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY and MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MRS MARGARET BECKETT, front-running candidate for Labour's deputy
leadership, may win the post in the first ballot of the July 18 election,
many of her opponents now concede.
Yesterday the shadow chief secretary's office released results from 11
constituency parties indicating the 'dream ticket' - with Mr John Smith, as
leader - as the outcome.
But the claims provoked a vituperative response from Mr Bryan Gould, shadow
environment secretary and candidate for the posts of both leader and deputy.
Speaking in East Ham, Mr Gould clearly targeted Mrs Beckett and Mr John
Prescott, his rivals for the deputy leadership, for failing to help open up
the debate on Labour's future.
'A premature election, a ridiculous electoral college and campaigns that
have done their best to avoid a political debate have done the Labour party
no service at all,' he said. He added: 'Candidates have put more effort into
claims of how well they are doing and rubbishing how well other candidates
are doing than into giving reasons why they should be elected.'
The post-mortem into the general election defeat, due at a special meeting
of the national executive on Thursday, had become 'a personalised game of
hunt the scapegoat' instead of looking at why Labour lost by a huge 7 per
cent deficit.
Supporters of Mr Gould claimed the speech was deliberately intended to fire
up the leadership campaign and provoke a wider debate on the party's future.
However, it is certain to raise serious doubts as to whether Mr Gould can
now expect an important portfolio from Mr Smith when he forms his shadow
cabinet.
One Labour MP close to the Gould camp has privately admitted that there
seems little chance that Labour's environment spokesman will pass the first
hurdle and force Mrs Beckett to a second ballot.
At the GMB general union's annual conference in Blackpool yesterday, Mr
Smith reiterated his backing for a fundamental review of links with the
unions underpinned by one-person, one-vote principles. He also indicated
support for a longer timetable on reform than many Labour activists
envisaged.
The review would to begin in earnest after the leadership elections on July
18 with final recommendations to go to the party's conference in the autumn
of next year.
</TEXT>
