<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JUN 92 / Hopes rise for Ulster talks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A FLURRY of activity by diplomats, politicians and civil servants yesterday
followed what may prove to have been a breakthrough in Northern Ireland's
politics.
Preparations are under way for a meeting that will bring Unionists face to
face with the government of the Irish Republic for the first time since
partition in the 1920s. Plans are being laid for the UK and the republic to
start work on a replacement for the 1985 Anglo-Irish agreement.
However, the worth of a deal struck by Sir Patrick Mayhew, Northern Ireland
secretary, with local politicians just before midnight on Friday is not yet
clear. Officials in London and Dublin have kept tight control on information
with no details of any meetings being released.
Perhaps the biggest clue yesterday was an air of optimism among government
officials in London and Dublin, and no sign of a breach in the participants'
vow of silence.
For seven weeks Unionists and nationalists have been discussing proposals
for devolution in Northern Ireland. This was Strand One. Little progress has
been made but the agreement struck before talks began was that 'within
weeks' negotiations would turn to Strand Two, when the republic would enter
to discuss relations between north and south.
Sir Patrick could have suspended the talks or forced a move to Strand Two
with Strand One in disarray. Lengthy deliberations followed.
Unionists, particularly the Rev Ian Paisley, leader of the Democratic
Unionist party, said Strand One had to be completed. The nationalist Social
Democratic and Labour party argued that the 'totality of relationships' in
Northern Ireland had to be addressed and that a move to Strand Two would
help to solve Strand One.
Sir Patrick's answer was a complex compromise. Strand Two is not about to
start, but the proposed independent chairman - Sir Ninian Stephen, former
governor-general of Australia - will convene a meeting this week in London,
probably on Wednesday, to discuss a possible agenda for Strand Two. Junior
representatives of the two governments and the main political parties will
attend.
Meanwhile, the British and Irish governments will meet, according to the
official statement, 'to give preliminary consideration to the issues likely
to arise' in the third and final strand - on Anglo-Irish relations,
principally the 1985 pact.
With the duration of the talks limited - the cut-off point is a meeting of
the Anglo-Irish conference at the end of next month - excessive time-wasting
has been avoided, and discussions will continue. Sir Patrick may regard that
as a breakthrough in itself.
</TEXT>
