FT  16 JUN 92 / Courts Charter to be issued later in year
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE, Legal Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Courts Charter, which is due to be discussed at the prime minister's
six-monthly seminar on the Citizens' Charter on Friday, is not likely to be
ready for publication before the end of the summer.
The Lord Chancellor's department, which with the Crown Prosecution Service
is responsible for drawing up the new charter guaranteeing standards of
service and facilities for court users, said yesterday it was still at an
early draft stage.
The Lord Chancellor's Department is one of only a handful of government
departments which has yet to publish information about standards of public
service in its area as part of the charter initiative.
The Justice Charter for Scotland, which sets out the standards of service
which all users of the Scottish justice system can expect and what will be
done if services do not come up to standard, was published as early as last
November.
The English charter is likely to be modelled on the Scottish version. It
sets standards of service for the police, courts, prosecuting authorities
and prison service and describes the action being taken to improve the
quality of services.
</TEXT>
