FT  16 JUN 92 / Stock market looks at plans for new capital
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Stock Exchange is considering plans to raise new capital, probably from
continental European brokers and investors, it said yesterday.
Mr Peter Rawlins, chief executive, said that the exchange wanted to spread
the costs of financing the development of new technology more widely. The
brokers and marketmakers who own the exchange are under financial pressure
and are finding it difficult to pass on the costs of the exchange to their
customers.
Also, Mr Rawlins said, they are concerned that they are being forced to pay
for developments which one day will benefit other users of the market.
In the past year the exchange has spent Pounds 25m on Taurus, its
long-delayed settlement system, bringing total spending so far to nearly
Pounds 50m. It also plans an overhaul of the systems that support trading.
The Stock Exchange said it had yet to develop any firm proposals on how it
could raise more capital. However, it seems unlikely that it would attempt
to sell shares to investors with no direct interest in the exchange. With
its declared aim of remaining a non-profit institution, it cannot pay a
market rate of return.
One exchange executive said: 'The scope for profit-making is not great in
the UK market. There are so many legal and regulatory matters that would get
in the way.'
The alternative would be to tempt securities brokers and others on the
Continent to join the exchange. However, since it operates an electronic
market, the exchange cannot sell seats to brokers to raise cash.
The exchange's operating costs fell from Pounds 182m to Pounds 171m during
the year, largely as a result of staff reductions. Its income climbed by
Pounds 9.5m to Pounds 194m, reflecting increases in settlement income as
trading volumes climbed.
After a review of its properties, the exchange lowered the valuation of for
its headquarters building in the City by Pounds 20m to Pounds 90m.
Observer Page 21
Lex, Page 22
</TEXT>
