<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JUN 92 / Warning issued on software taxation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS and ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COMPANIES that write their own software could find their tax position under
attack from the Inland Revenue, Sir Andrew Hugh Smith, chairman of the Stock
Exchange, warned yesterday.
The exchange itself is being challenged by the Revenue over its practice of
writing off all the costs of software development in the year they are
incurred. Last year that amounted to Pounds 25m, all of it spent on Taurus,
the planned new settlement system.
The Revenue has challenged the exchange, arguing that software development
costs are a form of capital spending. As such, these costs should only be
eligible for capital allowances, which amount to 25 per cent of the spending
in the first year.
If applied to all companies that generate their own software, the rule could
prevent companies claiming immediate tax relief on significant costs.
The Computer Services Association, a trade association, estimates that
companies spend Pounds 3bn to Pounds 4bn a year on developing software for
their own use.
Sir Andrew warned that the ruling would be particularly costly for financial
institutions, which spend large sums on software development.
'This will have quite an effect on the level of investment in the City as a
whole,' he said.
According to Mr John Barnsley, head of tax at Price Waterhouse, the
accountancy firm, companies have, however, increasingly been switching to
capitalising their software development spending, rather than writing it off
in the year it is incurred,
The escalating cost of developing computer systems, and the impact of the
recession in reducing profits, means that many companies are reluctant to
write off their development costs in the year in which they are incurred.
</TEXT>
