<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JUN 92 / Unexpected lifeline for Maxwell victims: John Willman sees
some hope for pensioners if they can pierce government secrecy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NEWS that intelligence information suggested the dishonesty of Robert
Maxwell before his empire collapsed offers the Maxwell pensioners another
lifeline in their campaign for government compensation.
Their chances of persuading the government to accept full responsibility for
bailing out the Maxwell pension funds will be enhanced if it can be shown
that government departments failed to act on information which revealed
Maxwell's questionable activities.
The pensioners' problem will be to establish that such information was in
the government's hands.
The response of the Maxwell Pensioners Action Group to yesterday's FT
revelations was to call for a judicial inquiry to examine the affair and
identify the failings of the system. The pensioners' best chance of
compensation probably lies with Mr William Reid, the parliamentary
commissioner known as the ombudsman. The 1989 report of his predecessor, Sir
Anthony Barrowclough, unlocked government funds for 18,000 investors who
lost money when the Barlow Clowes group collapsed.
Sir Anthony found the Department of Trade and Industry guilty of
'significant maladministration'. He criticised 'the lack of a sufficiently
rigorous and inquiring approach', including the inadequacy of the regulatory
machinery before April 1988 when the Financial Services Act was introduced.
Announcing the payment in the Commons, Lord Ridley, then trade and industry
secretary, justified compensation by the 'number of unusual features which
taken together distinguish this case from other business failures'. Lord
Ridley, then Mr Nicholas Ridley, added: 'It is also true that a large number
of investors, many of them elderly, have suffered hardship'.
There are clear similarities with the present case in the age of many
Maxwell pensioners and the hardship they will suffer without compensation.
But the pensioners will need to work hard to establish a case the ombudsman
can consider, because the looting of the Maxwell pension funds took place
after the introduction of the 1988 Financial Services Act.
That act switched responsibility for policing the pension funds from the DTI
to the Securities and Investments Board (SIB) and the Investment Management
Regulatory Organisation (Imro), both of which are excluded from the
jurisdiction of the ombudsman. As the current ombudsman pointed out 10 days
ago, he cannot launch an investigation without evidence of an administrative
fault by a government department.
One such fault might be that the powers delegated by the DTI to SIB and Imro
did not adequately protect the interests of pension fund managers. To
establish a case for the ombudsman to investigate, pensioners would need to
show that representations had been made when the powers were delegated and
that they were ignored or brushed aside.
An ombudsman's investigation might also be triggered if it could be shown
that the government had had information about Mr Maxwell's questionable
activities - from the intelligence services, for example - and failed to
pass it on to the regulatory authorities.
It would be hard to prove either of these faults without access to documents
in government files. Yet under the UK's secretive system of government, they
are not open to public inspection.
Hence the Maxwell pensioners' call for a judicial inquiry into the affair.
In spite of the prime minister's commitment to more open government, the
only way to cast more light on the proceedings of government in cases such
as this is to appoint a judge or a privy councillor to examine all relevant
papers.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
