<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JUN 92 / Treasury moves to sell off debt
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SECURITIES houses are being invited by the Treasury to bid for Pounds 5bn of
government debt that remains with privatised industries.
One securities house said yesterday that several City institutions had been
asked to look at ways of repackaging parcels of debt owed to the government,
mainly by British Telecommunications and the electricity distributors.
The transfer of the debts - incurred in the run-up to privatisation - would
release to the Treasury revenue that would otherwise have been repaid over
almost 20 years.
The revenue injection would count as negative government spending and
therefore cut the size of the public sector borrowing requirement.
The Treasury would not confirm that it had plans to sell debt, but officials
said it would be possible to sell the rights to it and to raise a lump sum.
'We would simply need to find somebody who would be prepared to buy the
rights to receive the debt,' said a Treasury official. 'Most of the debt is
potentially marketable, but some of it isn't'
BT still has to pay off just under Pounds 2.2bn, while the electricity
distribution companies owe about Pounds 1.2bn. Further smaller stocks of
debt from the generating companies, the Scottish electricity companies and
National Television Licensing brings the total still owed to the Treasury to
just over Pounds 5bn.
The debt, which is in the form of debentures and loan stock, was to be
repaid over a number of years. For example, British Gas made its last
repayment of Pounds 350m in April.
The debt should be relatively easy to buy and sell, but its transfer to bond
markets might make it harder for the privatised companies to raise capital
subsequently in a market where there is only a finite demand for sterling
bonds.
</TEXT>
