<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JUN 92 / UN troops may take airport by end of week: Boutros Ghali
will recommend deployment of 1,000 Canadians if fragile ceasefire holds
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUDY DEMPSEY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BELGRADE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
CANADIAN troops could take control of Sarajevo airport by the end of the
week if the fragile ceasefire, which came into force yesterday morning,
continues to hold.
But a United Nations official who forged the ceasefire agreement between the
Bosnian presidency and Serb irregulars yesterday said: 'Anything could go
wrong.
'We are relying on the good will of all sides to enforce the ceasefire. This
is a real cliffhanger,' he added.
Yesterday, French airport security officials who are working with the UN in
Sarajevo, again visited the airport. They said it was not badly damaged by
Serb irregulars who have blockaded the airport for the past 10 weeks, and
have prevented food and medical supplies reaching Sarajevo.
UN officials want to use the ceasefire to start de-militarising the airport,
and its surrounding areas.
If the ceasefire holds, UN secretary general Boutros Boutros Ghali will
early this week recommend that the security council deploy 1,000 Canadian
troops equipped with 80 armoured personnel carriers, to take over the
airport.
Yesterday, the city's inhabitants emerged from their cellars into the
pouring rain, but few have high hopes in any lasting ceasefire.
'I do not believe in it. The Serb irregulars are already sniping,' said Mr
Kemal Kurpasic, editor of Oslobedjne, the Bosnia daily newspaper. 'If they
keep sniping, the Territorial Defence might be forced to respond,' he added.
As he spoke by telephone from his apartment, a bullet ripped through his
kitchen wall. 'You see what I mean. This is a very fragile ceasefire,' said
Mr Kurpasic.
Mr Zlatan Cabaravdiz, a journalist at Sarajevo radio, said both sides were
weighting up the advantages in maintaining the ceasefire.
'We have seen ceasefires come and go,' he said. 'With this one, the Serb
irregulars can re-group, and withdraw to the hills surrounding the city.
They can shell and divide the city at any time. What would you expect the
Territorial Defence to do then? Do you expect them to withdraw from the
positions they already hold in Sarajevo?' he asked.
Mr Kurpasic and western diplomats said the Serb irregulars, and Serbia's
proxy army in Bosnia were using the ceasefire and international attention on
Sarajevo as 'a smokescreen.'
'There are awful things happening in other towns and cities which are being
besieged and where the killing never stops,' Mr Kurpasic said.
Yesterday, western diplomats said Croat forces from Croatia were
consolidating their own positions in Derventa, north of Bosnia, and in
Mostar, east of the republic, despite repeated requests by the UN to
Croatian president Franjo Tudjman to withdraw his forces from Bosnia.
In Belgrade, the Serbian capital, about 10,000 students staged a peaceful
demonstration against Serbian president Slobodan Milosevic, who has not been
seen, or heard, for several days.
Yesterday, Mr Dobrica Cosic, an ultra Serb nationalist, was elected the
president of the new Yugoslavia, in a move likely to give the nationalists
far greater say, and power, over the coming weeks.
</TEXT>
