<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JUN 92 / Major pressed on Maxwell intelligence claims
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH, PHILIP STEPHENS, JIMMY BURNS and RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SENIOR Labour spokesmen yesterday demanded a full inquiry into the extent of
the government's knowledge of Robert Maxwell's activities before the
collapse of his business empire.
Mr Gordon Brown, the shadow trade secretary, wrote to Mr John Major urging
him to set up an inquiry. His letter follows yesterday's Financial Times
report that the government was in possession of intelligence information at
least two years before the death of Maxwell suggesting he had been acting
dishonestly.
Whitehall officials did not deny that Maxwell's telephone or other
activities had been monitored. But they said there was no evidence to
suggest that ministers had seen information which might have alerted them to
fraud in the Maxwell empire. Mr Major was certain that he had seen nothing
either as chancellor or prime minister.
Mr Brown said he was seeking a statement on 'who was informed, when and in
what detail, and - specifically - why no action was taken to investigate
fraud and protect pension funds'.
However, Miss Ann Widdecombe, junior social security minister, ruled out a
fresh investigation and rejected calls for another Commons debate or
government statement. 'It would be quite counter-productive to react every
day to every new twist of the Maxwell saga,' she said on Channel Four News.
Commenting specifically on the allegations in yesterday's FT, she said: 'The
government has already made very clear statements to the effect that we do
not believe that we have any responsibility for what happened.'
Mr Richard Page, Conservative co-chairman of the all-party group of MPs
campaigning on behalf of the Maxwell pensioners, said: 'If it turns out the
government knew that Maxwell was bleeding money out of the pension funds,
then the pressure on the government to provide for the pensioners becomes
almost irresistible.'
The FT yesterday quoted Mr Robin Robison, who in June 1988 became an
administrative officer for the Joint Intelligence Committee, part of the
Cabinet Office which assesses information from Britain's intelligence
services.
Last night Mr Peter Thompson, a former editor of the Sunday Mirror and
director of Mirror Group Newspapers, said that a book he co-authored in 1988
was suppressed by Maxwell partly because it had originally claimed that the
British security services had extensive files on the publisher.
The FT has confirmed separately, from a source other than Mr Robison or Mr
Thompson, that intelligence information on Maxwell's activities had been
available for some years. A full intelligence report on Maxwell was prepared
from files for the JIC at the time of his death on November 5 last year.
Mr Robison - a Quaker who was positively vetted by the security services in
1987 - claimed that in 1989 he saw intelligence information on Maxwell from
intercepted telephone conversations and faxes. The information, he said, had
been distributed to Whitehall officials including the prime minister's
office.
Senior Whitehall officials disputed that Mr Robison could have seen signals
intelligence information in autumn 1989, as he claimed. They said Mr Robison
was moved from his JIC work in June 1989 to another post in the Cabinet
Office. After that he had no further access to secret material. Downing
Street indicated that there were no plans to seek a prosecution of Mr
Robison under the Official Secrets Act.
Mr Robison said last night he resigned from the Cabinet Office at the end of
January 1990. He insisted he continued to have access to top-secret material
after June 1989.
There was no comment in Whitehall on the suggestion that intelligence
services might have been routinely collecting information on the Maxwell
empire. The government's policy is not to discuss the work of the security
services, though it is acknowledged that commercial activities do fall
within their remit.
Discussing the suppression of the book he co-authored with Mr Anthony
Delano, Mr Thompson said last night: 'Maxwell was particularly angry about a
passage which detailed the files which MI5 had on him. I have no reason to
believe that the information about the file and the dossiers was
inaccurate.'
According to Mr Thompson, Maxwell objected to a claim that a former MI5
agent saw no fewer than 37 assembled dossiers on the publisher. The book,
Maxwell: A Portrait of Power, was published in February 1988. But Maxwell's
lawyers obtained an injunction to prevent further sales and issued writs for
defamation. After an out-of-court settlement the hardback copies were
withdrawn and pulped. A paperback version published since Maxwell's death
did not include the passages in question.
In the Commons, Mr Michael Meacher, shadow social security secretary,
questioned why, if the government had such information before 1989, the
Department of Trade and Industry had nonetheless granted investment licences
to two Maxwell companies, which he later used to pillage the pension funds.
However, Miss Widdecombe said last night the crucial question was not to ask
what had happened but how to prevent a repetition of the suffering of
Maxwell pensioners.
Asked whether the government would put pressure on Liechtenstein in the
search for Maxwell funds, she said: 'The government will do what is
appropriate as and when it believes action is necessary.'
Arise, King of Bulgaria, Page 9
Unexpected lifeline; MGN seeks Dollars 86m from Daily News, Page 10
Invesco denial, Page 24
