liquidation in New York ahead of July's first notice day tomorrow. There
appeared to be no sign of any major selling by producers, but the prospect
of further sales continued to weigh on sentiment. Dealers said signs of
increased flexibility from Brazil at producer talks in Ivory Coast were seen
as mildly constructive. On the LME solid buying interest helped keep TIN'S
upward momentum intact, with three-month prices hitting a new 25-month high
of Dollars 6,590 a tonne. Many expect prices to hit an upside objective of
Dollars 7,000 by the end of the month.
