<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JUN 92 / UK Company News: Household Mortgage more than doubles to
Pounds 5.16m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BARCHARD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HOUSEHOLD Mortgage Corporation, the privately-owned residential mortgage
company, yesterday upstaged larger lenders by more than doubling its pre-tax
profits in the year to March 31 despite the housing market recession.
In one of the strongest performances in the housing finance industry in
1991, HMC's taxable profits for the 12 months surged from Pounds 2.21m to
Pounds 5.16m. Interest receivable rose from Pounds 228.43m to Pounds
258.66m, while other operating income was up from Pounds 4.87m to Pounds
9.45m.
Bad debt provisions remained relatively modest by the standards of other
lenders at Pounds 4.16m, though sharply up from Pounds 2.2m last time.
Operating expenses were up from Pounds 15.78m to Pounds 20.2m.
Total assets of Pounds 2bn were unchanged from last year and the customer
base was maintained at 40,000. During the year HMC increased its asset base
by purchasing mortgage books from several other lenders, including Westpac
and Boston Safe.
Mr Maxwell Packe, finance director, said the increase in profits reflected a
decision taken in the early stages of the recession by the company to
concentrate on top quality customers.
The 13 institutions which own HMC will be paid a dividend of 4.5 per cent,
totalling Pounds 1.4m.
A spokesman for the company said yesterday that HMC's long term plans
included a possible stock market flotation when the housing market had
recovered.
</TEXT>
