FT  16 JUN 92 / UK Company News: Fall in demand cuts Wellman to Pounds 1.05m
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
WELLMAN, the broadly-based engineering group, saw its pre-tax profit fall
almost Pounds 2m from Pounds 2.96m to Pounds 1.05m in the year ended March
31 1992, after reorganisation costs of Pounds 400,000.
The dividend is again 2.2p with a proposed final of 1.4p, and is just
covered by fully diluted earnings of 2.4p, compared with 6.3p.
Mr Geoffrey Iley, chairman, said all parts of the group experienced lower
activity levels.
Wellman Process and Wellman Bibby achieved higher profits although that did
not offset a significantly lower contribution from Cadogan as British
Aerospace partially withdrew work from sub-contractors.
Demand for furnace equipment remained depressed and Wellman Furnaces
suffered a loss of Pounds 240,000 before reorganisation.
The attributable profit fell from Pounds 2.17m to Pounds 262,000 after
taking into account Pounds 547,000 extraordinary charges relating to costs
of withdrawing from two low margin businesses.
Turnover slumped from Pounds 33m to Pounds 24m. Forward order book at March
31 was similar to last year, and had since been enhanced by the acquisition
of Midcast.
