FT  16 JUN 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Four new series start tonight. Borderlands (8.00 C4) is about six regions of
Europe affected by economic and political changes, starting with Catalonia
in north eastern Spain. As in so many regions on the periphery of larger,
more powerful states, the language, culture and history of Catalonia were
long suppressed.
Firm Friends (9.00 ITV) is a four-part drama in which Billie Whitelaw plays
a suburban housewife who sets up in the catering business with her Asian
cleaning lady. Madhur Jaffrey who plays this part is, of course, known at
least as well for her cookery books as for her acting.
Town Hall (9.50 BBC2) is an eight-part documentary series about the ins and
outs of local government, made by Malcolm Hirst and producer/cameraman
Charles Stewart who specialise in fly-on-the-wall work. The series was made
in the Labour controlled London borough of Lewisham.
Seven Up - Japan (10.40 ITV) extends the idea used so successfully by
Granada in Britain of filming a group of children at seven year intervals to
see how their lives progress. Similar long terms sequences made in Germany
and South Africa follow.
