FT  16 JUN 92 / Parliament and Politics: Penalty planned for Malmo hooligans
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ENGLISH soccer fans convicted of criminal offences at the European football
championships in Sweden could be banned from home games, Mr David Mellor,
national heritage secretary, told the Commons yesterday, David Owen writes.
Those convicted in Sweden 'can be prohibited from entering' UK football
grounds, Mr Mellor warned, adding that serious charges arising from the
events in Malmo had already been laid. 'I certainly hope we shall be able to
exclude those convicted from going to football matches again for a very long
time,' he said.
Mr Mellor, who was addressing his first session of Commons questions in his
new position, endured some spirited barracking from a small contingent of
Scottish MPs when he appeared initially to designate the misbehaving
supporters as 'British'.
Reprimanding the minister for his thoughtlessness, Mr Norman Godman, the
Labour MP for Greenock and Port Glasgow, pointed out that there were 'no
Scots anywhere near Malmo'.
He said: 'Not a single Scottish fan has got into any trouble.'
</TEXT>
