<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JUN 92 / Parliament and Politics: Pounds 100m pledged to global fund
for environment
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN IS to earmark Pounds 100m of new money for environmental spending
over a number of years to help replenish the Global Environment Facility, Mr
John Major, the prime minister, told the Commons yesterday.
He admitted, however, that the timescale over which the money would be made
available was indefinite and depended on when the fund - which is used by
the World Bank and the United Nations to help third world countries to
finance environmentally friendly projects - required it.
Reporting back on his return from the Earth Summit in Rio, Mr Major said it
was a 'milestone' while acknowledging that the results had not gone 'as far
as some would wish'.
He said that Britain itself could have 'gone further' on climate change than
the convention provides. Without the intervention of his ministerial
colleagues, however, 'there might not have been a climate convention to
sign'.
He said he had written to other EC heads of government and the G7 leading
industrial nations proposing an 'action plan' to carry forward commitments
made at Rio.
On broader subjects, he said he hoped that other G7 nations would adopt the
Trinidad terms on third world debt by the end of this year, and claimed that
agreement in the current General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade talks was
nearer 'than anyone realises or anyone imagined just a few weeks ago'. He
said he wanted to see the talks reach a conclusion by the end of this month,
'beyond which I think we run into timetabling troubles with the US
presidential election'.
Mr Roy Hattersley, Labour deputy leader, urged Mr Major to exploit Britain's
'special relationship' with the US to persuade president George Bush to sign
the biodiversity agreement on protecting rare plants and animals.
</TEXT>
