<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JUN 92 / Executive loses appeal over ban
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND HUGHES, Law Courts Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A FORMER company chair-man who was jailed last year for insider dealing has
failed to overturn an order disqualifying him from acting as a company
director for 10 years.
Mr Ivor Goodman, former chairman of Unigroup, the quoted Leeds-based timber
and clothing company, is the only person prosecuted for insider dealing in
the UK who has served a jail term for the offence. In April last year he
pleaded guilty at St Albans Crown Court to an offence under the Company
Securities (Insider Dealing) Act.
He was sentenced to 18 months, of which nine months were suspended. As he
had been in custody for five months, having been arrested for failing to
appear for trial the previous year, he had only four months left to serve.
In the event, because of remission, he was released a few days after being
sentenced.
Yesterday he challenged the disqualification order imposed on him under the
Company Directors (Disqualification) Act as part of his sentence.
Dismissing his appeal, Lord Justice Staughton said in the Court of Appeal
that Mr Goodman's offence was 'a monstrous and scandalous example of insider
trading'. Mr Goodman, the chairman of a public company had obtained, or
attempted to obtain, a very large sum.
'It is hard to think of a worse case,' the judge said.
At the trial the Department of Trade and Industry alleged that Mr Goodman
disposed of his 690,209 Unigroup shares - a substantial proportion of the
equity - just before the company announced worse-than-expected figures in
October 1987. He purported to give the holding to his girlfriend and it was
sold for 167p per share, netting Mr Goodman just under Pounds 1.2m.
The sale, and Mr Goodman's resignation as Unigroup's chairman, occurred a
few days before the Stock Exchange suspended the company's shares at its own
request. When dealings were resumed five months later the shares traded at
55p.
Chase Manhattan Securities, Unigroup's broker, confirmed in November 1987
that it had acquired the shares. Civil proceedings later resulted in the
share sale being set aside.
</TEXT>
