<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JUN 92 / Venture financing recovers slowly
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT, Midlands Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE VENTURE capital market in the west Midlands is slowly recovering, but
most finance is directed at corporate restructuring, particularly management
buy-outs, fund managers have reported.
Mr Alan Lewis, regional director of County NatWest Ventures, said higher
demand for development capital as companies sought equity to finance
expansion out of recession - a trend expected since the general election -
had not taken place to any marked degree. That indicated 'the recovery is a
slow and painful process at best'.
3i, the UK's largest venture capital group, has seen its activity decline
since the pre-election period, although it is committing more funds to
management buyouts.
Mr Chris Rowlands, Birmingham director of 3i, said in financial terms that
meant 'our activity is very strong, but it is not an accurate reflection of
underlying economic activity'.
Fund managers explained that the low demand for development capital
reflected nervousness not only about the state of order books but also about
strict bank policies.
Only 10 per cent of a Pounds 20m fund set up last August by 3i for small
inner-city businesses in the west Midlands had been taken up, Mr Rowlands
said.
Mr Brian Blakemore, regional director of Barclays Development Capital, said
the main emphasis had been in two categories - 'groups divesting of
subsidiaries because they have a need for cash, and family businesses where
outside management has been brought in and which now wants to buy'.
Nevertheless, whereas some venture capitalists did no deals in the first
quarter of last year, now they are bringing to fruition schemes put on ice
in the months before the election.
</TEXT>
