<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JUN 92 / Japanese MPs end long fight to let troops serve abroad
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEFAN WAGSTYL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
JAPAN'S DIET yesterday ended a long legislative battle and passed a
controversial bill to allow Japanese troops to serve in United Nations
peacekeeping forces.
The bill, which has caused deep divisions in Japan, authorises the first
despatch of Japanese soldiers overseas since the second world war. Their
first assignment is likely to be on the UN's peacekeeping mission in
Cambodia.
The bill was passed by 329 votes to 17 in the Diet's 512-seat lower house in
spite of intense opposition by the Social Democratic and Communist parties.
The social democrats boycotted the proceedings in a last-ditch effort to
block the bill and tendered their resignations en masse.
Mr Makoto Tanabe, Social Democratic party chairman, said the bill would
leave a 'deep scar' on Japan. Mr Kiichi Miyazawa, prime minister, hailed the
bill, saying Japan would be able to send personnel on UN missions.
The bill's origins date back to the Gulf crisis, when the government mooted
the idea of sending Japanese troops to serve in non-combat roles in the
US-led coalition forces.
But the proposals were dropped after arousing public protest, with many
Japanese saying that sending troops abroad, even on UN missions, would
infringe the country's pacifist constitution. Asian countries, notably
China, also expressed concern about a possible revival of Japanese
militarism.
New proposals were eventually passed by the lower house last December. The
bill authorises Japan to send up to 2,000 troops on UN missions. But they
may only serve in non-combatant roles unless the Diet revises the
legislation to allow for front-line duties.
The ruling Liberal Democratic party tried to accommodate opposition parties'
views by watering down the bill. But as parties jockeyed for position with
an eye on elections to the upper house at the end of July, the opposition
resorted to filibustering with a slow-voting technique called the ox-walk in
which members edged towards the ballot box an inch at a time.
A poll conducted at the weekend by TBS, a tele-vision station, showed 55 per
cent against the bill and 32 per cent in favour, with the rest undecided.
After all-night sessions, the bill passed the upper house and was returned
to the lower house for the approval of amendments. Yesterday the Social
Democratic party changed tack and all 137 of its members tendered their
resignations to the Speaker. It was unclear last night whether these
resignations would be accepted.
</TEXT>
