<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUN 92 / Monday Interview: Defender of a fine British line - Malcolm
Rifkind, defence secretary, talks to Robert Mauthner and David White
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT MAUTHNER and DAVID WHITE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Few members of the post-general election cabinet have settled in more
quickly - or more comfortably - into their new jobs than Mr Malcolm Rifkind
at the Ministry of Defence.
Draped elegantly on the office sofa in his shirt sleeves, the Secretary of
State gives the impression of having dealt with security and defence issues
for most of his life. His relaxed manner, coupled with one of the most
articulate intellects in Mr John Major's new team, are in sharp contrast to
that of the bustling and somewhat less ordered Tom King, his immediate
predecessor.
If the Scottish Office, Mr Rifkind's last but one portfolio, was a thistle
which even a native Scot sometimes found difficult to grasp, the MoD is not
very different in character. Though it may not be quite the ministerial
'ejector seat' that its German equivalent is reputed to be, it can be
something of a graveyard for political ambitions. Neither of Mr Rifkind's
two predecessors, Mr King and Mr George Younger, have continued their
ministerial careers.
The new defence secretary was thrown in at the deep end. Opponents of army
cuts seized on his appointment to fan speculation about plans to rescue some
of the Scottish regiments, condemned by Mr King's rationalisation measures.
But Mr Rifkind, in spite of his origins, seems determined not to reopen that
emotional debate.
Foreign mines also strewed his path. Hardly was he appointed, than Germany's
doubts about the European Fighter Aircraft (EFA) came to the boil,
threatening the imminent break-up of the venture (Spain and Italy are the
other partners).
While recognising, 'as a fellow politician', the parliamentary pressures on
the German government to withdraw from the project and making constructive
cost-cutting suggestions, he has not hesitated to speak his mind on the
consequences for European co-operation.
'I don't think it is possible for the German government, on the one hand to
speak robustly about the desirability of a European defence dimension and
European co-operation, and at the same time consider withdrawing from the
single most important example of European defence collaboration that exists
at the present time.'
That is tough talk from the representative of a country which has not
exactly distinguished itself by its enthusiasm for European collaborative
projects in other fields, such as space research. Nor does Mr Rifkind appear
at all put out by criticisms that Britain continues to be unduly
'Atlanticist' in its approach to European security problems.
Though he undoubtedly sees himself as 'a good European', Mr Rifkind's views
do not diverge an iota from the traditional British government line on
defence. That is based on the hallowed proposition that, whatever steps are
taken to deepen European defence co-operation, absolute priority must
continue to be given to the preservation of Nato as the principal
organisation responsible for Europe's defence. Only in this way can
Washington's commitment to the defence of Europe be guaranteed.
'The US shares with all European countries a desire to see better European
co-operation. There is no problem about the basic consideration of Europe
getting its act together more effectively. The question is whether the
practice of European co-operation is to strengthen the Atlantic alliance or
ultimately to weaken it.'
His main concern, Mr Rifkind went on, is not so much the view of the US
Administration, but how the signals sent from Europe were interpreted by
Congress and American public opinion as a whole. Any talk of a 'European
army' is bound to alienate the sensitive people on Capitol Hill and lead to
the very troop withdrawals that all America's European allies say they want
to avoid.
That said, Mr Rifkind is firm in his support of the British interpretation
of the formula on a common European security and, eventually, defence
policy, laid down in the Maastricht Treaty. The present furore over the
future of the treaty in no way invalidates the objective of developing a
European defence identity, he emphasises, because parallel decisions were
taken in other western forums at about the same time. The decision to
develop a European defence dimension via the Western European Union
(nine-nation defence organisation, pre-dating Nato), for instance, was taken
by the Rome Nato summit last November and was subsequently referred to in
the Maastricht communique.
'But, actually, in the legal sense, it was an independent decision. It is
precisely because the European Community does not have direct competence in
defence matters that they do not directly relate to the Maastricht Treaty.'
That is called killing two birds with one stone. In one short statement Mr
Rifkind has proclaimed both Britain's commitment to greater European defence
co-operation within Nato and its rejection of an independent EC defence
organisation - even in the long run.
The link that the French, and to some extent the Germans, believe should be
established between the EC's institutions and the WEU is recognised by Mr
Rifkind only in the broadest sense that both organisations 'are relevant to
the development of common European interests'.
He is quick to add, however, that 'there is no single authority which covers
both. There is no legal binding relationship between the two nor any
proposal that there should be so . . . the WEU itself takes its decisions
with regard to its own development and possible role.'
As for the practical measures required to give some substance to a new
European defence identity, such as the provision of forces for possible WEU
operations outside the Nato area, Mr Rifkind concedes, with a wry laugh,
that they do tend to be rather 'confusing'.
Britain's original idea of a European rapid reaction corps is basically
using Nato forces in another guise - 'double hatting' in the deceptively
jokey official jargon. This is very different from the French and German
concept of a 'European corps'.
Mr Rifkind does not oppose the Franco-German force in principle. It could be
one of a whole number of forces made available to WEU. But he has strong
reservations about the fact that it is made up of German forces which are
assigned to Nato and French forces which do not come under Nato's integrated
command. In short, he finds the German argument that the joint force will
bring France closer to Nato, from whose military structure the French
withdrew as long ago as 1966, less than convincing.
'As an aspiration, we can obviously see it as an attractive objective. But
if that is the reason for the Franco-German corps, then it would have been
the easiest thing in the world for the French government to make that
clear,' Mr Rifkind proclaims.
'Will the relationship between the Franco-German corps and Nato be the same
as the current German relationship (with Nato) or the current French
relationship? It must be one or the other, and the indication so far is that
the relationship would be closer to the current French than the current
German one. If that is true - and I say, if - then clearly we would have to
see the Franco-German corps as weakening Similar scepticism is displayed
about the possibility of giving the new European defence identity a nuclear
dimension, involving essentially nuclear co-operation between Britain and
France.
'I cannot conceive a foreseeable future situation in which the use of
nuclear forces did not point towards Nato responsibility. Obviously, we are
not averse to a closer French involvement in Nato at any time, whether it be
on nuclear or non-nuclear matters. Close co-operation between Britain and
France on nuclear defence very much depends on France's ongoing relationship
with Nato. In present circumstances, I think the French would rule it out.'
The British litmus test for European defence co-operation has thus been
forcefully restated by Mr Rifkind. It is likely to be modified only if the
US itself has a fundamental change of heart about its commitment to Europe.
PERSONAL FILE
1946 Born Edinburgh. Educated George Watson's College and Ediburgh
University.
1967 Lecturer in politics, University of Rhodesia.
1970 Called to the Scottish Bar.
1974 MP for Edinburgh Pentlands.
1979 Junior minister, Scottish Office.
1983 Minister of State, Foreign and Commonwealth Office.
1986 Secretary for Scotland.
1990 Secretary for Transport.
1992 Secretary for Defence.
