<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUN 92 / Labour to press for early reduction in interest rates
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY and EMMA TUCKER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN SMITH, the shadow chancellor and clear favourite for the Labour
leadership, will today press for a cut in interest rates as anxiety grows in
the government over the sluggishness of the long-predicted economic
recovery.
In an effort to maximise the government's discomfiture, Mr Smith will argue
that, with mounting unemployment and business failures, there is 'precious
little' evidence of the recovery the Conservatives had promised would follow
their April election victory.
His speech to the GMB general union in Blackpool criticises the government
for taking no action to stimulate production or demand: 'It is time now for
a further reduction in interest rates - a reduction which I believe can be
sustained within the exchange rate mechanism.
'After all what is the point of being in the wide, 6 per cent band, if the
greater latitude it offers is hardly ever used.'
Treasury officials believe, however, that the opportunity for the government
to stimulate demand by cutting interest rates has receded significantly
following Denmark's rejection of the Maastricht treaty on monetary union.
On Friday, sterling stood at DM2.92, three pfennings below its DM2.95
central rate in the ERM, while interest rates at 10 per cent are just a
quarter of a percentage point above the German Lombard rate.
Most independent economists also seem to concede that there is little margin
for flexibility. Private sector economists have revised their expectations
for economic growth this year to less than the 1 per cent forecast by Mr
Norman Lamont, the chancellor, in his March Budget.
The lacklustre outlook for the economy is provoking disquiet among
Conservative MPs, with the Euro-sceptic faction seizing on the Danish
referendum result to step up its attacks on the UK's ERM membership as an
intolerable constraint.
Meanwhile, ministers last week completed their submissions to Mr Michael
Portillo, the chief secretary to the Treasury, for spending in the coming
fiscal year.
In spite of an early round of meetings with Mr Portillo, aimed at ramming
home the government's call for austerity, the rise in unemployment levels
alone means that at least Pounds 1bn more will be needed to pay benefits.
