<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUN 92 / UN worried over Serbian plans: Ethnic groups will be split
apart if division of Sarajevo goes ahead
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUDY DEMPSEY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BELGRADE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
UNITED NATIONS and European Community officials are increasingly concerned
that Mr Radovan Karadzic, head of Bosnia's Serb community, will press ahead
with a plan to divide the besieged city of Sarajevo along ethnic lines.
The plan, which the UN and EC have consistently opposed, would involve the
transfer of residents into ethnically-homogenous sectors. It would be
carried out irrespective of any ceasefire.
A green line, modelled on the one which divided Beirut for many years, would
run north-south through Sarajevo, with Serb irregulars holding the western
half of the city. Much of the recent fighting has been concentrated along
the north, centre, and west of the city in what western diplomats say is an
attempt to drive out the local population.
Dividing Sarajevo, which before Serb irregulars laid siege to it nine weeks
ago had a population of 525,000, would mean the mixed ethnic communities of
Moslems, Serbs and Croats, and those from mixed marriages who have
co-existed for centuries, would be forced to choose which part of the divide
they would live in. An estimated 200,000 people have already fled the city.
Western diplomats said Mr Karadzic has repeatedly tried to link the
re-opening of the city's airport - controlled by Serb irregulars so as to
prevent food from reaching the starving people of Sarajevo - with the
division of the city.
Any such linkage has been repeatedly rejected by UN officials. The UN's
primary task in securing control of the airport is to facilitate the
unhindered supply of food and humanitarian aid into Sarajevo.
'This plan by Karadzic is sheer madness. We are talking about another
Beirut. But Karadzic refuses to let go of this idea. Somehow he sees it as
his historical mission, on behalf of Serbs, to divide the city, and give it
to the Serbs, even if it means completely destroying large parts of Sarajevo
in the process,' a western diplomat said.
Mr Karadzic originally drew up the plans to divide Sarajevo on the basis
that it would merge with Serb-controlled areas in central and eastern
Bosnia. Those areas, which would then be linked to Serbia, which borders
with Bosnia-Hercegovina, would form Greater Serbia.
He has the full backing of Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic, who,
despite his attempt to convince the international community that Serbia no
longer supports the Bosnian Serbs, continues to send arms, money, and
logistical backing to Mr Karadzic and General Ratko Mladic, commander of
Serbia's proxy army in Bosnia.
Western diplomats say Mr Karadzic will continue to bombard Sarajevo to
establish his green line, even if Mr Milosevic drops his Greater Serbia
plan.
'The point is that if, and when, all this fighting is over, the desire for
revenge among all ethnic groups in Sarajevo, and Bosnia, will be intense,' a
senior western diplomat said.
'Karadzic realises this. He knows that those Serbs who participated in the
siege of Sarajevo will never be safe to walk the streets of that city again.
'Karadzic also wants the green line for his own security, and for those
Serbs who choose to live there, even if that means creating a ghetto, or a
kind of east Berlin which will never be recognised by the international
community.'
Hopes for relief, Page 2
