<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUN 92 / Observer: Old school
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Still on the subject of the City's old training schools, Bryan Quinton of
Invesco MIM has solved Observer's request for information on how many
Conservative MPs honed their early business skills inside the Slater Walker
empire which collapsed so spectacularly in the mid-1970s.
Quinton, who was Jim Slater's first employee, has counted six ex-colleagues
still making their way up the political ladder: Sir John Cope (paymaster
general), Tony Nelson (economic secretary), Alastair Goodlad (foreign
office) and Jonathan Aitken (defence) have made it to ministerial rank,
while Alan Haselhurst and John Butterfill carry the torch on the back
benches.
Admittedly, none of them comes close to matching the success of Lord (Peter)
Walker, Jim Slater's first deputy chairman. But unless one counts Lords
Hanson and Sterling, who in their early days benefited from Jim Slater's
charisma, far more Slater Walker old boys seem to have made their mark in
politics, rather than the City.
A subject for an explanatory doctoral thesis, perhaps?
