FT  15 JUN 92 / Observer: Balanced view
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
It says much for the sheer doggedness of the Basle-based Bank for
International Settlements that when it comes to debating Europe's monetary
and economic union, it's still talking in terms of when, rather than if, it
happens.
The central bankers' bank was certainly not going to allow the rebellious
Danes to disrupt its long-planned discussion of the non-European view of EMU
at yesterday's BIS annual meeting. Indeed, scores of central bankers from as
far away places as India and Mexico were invited to the closed session.
Luckily, Erik Hoffmeyer, chairman of the Committee of European Community
Central Bank Governors, was on hand to give his advice. Not only is he
attempting to pick up the pieces of EMU after the Danish referendum result,
but he is also the governor of the Danish Central Bank.
Yesterday the amiable Danish bank chief was doing his best to shrug off any
possible discomfort and insisting that the Danish vote had been the result
of a fair and proper debate.
