<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUN 92 / Observer: Trouble shooter
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Who is going to replace Sir John Cuckney? Observer poses the question
following the news that Sir John has been hired yet again to try and clean
up another lovely City mess - recovering the Maxwell missing millions for
the unfortunate pensioners.
Over the last couple of decades, Sir John has carved out a reputation for
himself as the man who can be relied upon to sort out financial
mismanagement or skulduggery in both the public and private sectors. The
Mersey Docks and Harbour Board, Westland, Crown Agents, John Brown, the Port
of London Authority, are just a few of the casualties who have had the
Cuckney treatment.
Now Sir John has been made chairman of the trust for Maxwell pensioners and
has the unenviable task of persuading the private sector to cough up. If
anyone can do it, he can, given his network of contacts. As an old
intelligence hand, he should know where the skeletons are hidden and even if
he doesn't he is rather good at twisting arms for the public good.
Nevertheless, Sir John turns 67 next month and has already started to shed a
heavy City work load. He remains chairman of Royal Insurance but steps down
from 3i next month. Sooner or later someone else is going to have to do Sir
John's dirty work. Suggestions to Number 10 and the Bank of England, please.
</TEXT>
