<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUN 92 / A game of missed opportunities: Though the Rio Earth Summit
fell short of its goals, it served a useful purpose
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LASCELLES and CHRISTINA LAMB
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
If for no other reason, the Earth Summit will go down in history as an
astonishing political event. At tea-time on Saturday afternoon, no fewer
than 103 world leaders sat down at a huge round table in the Riocentro and
solemnly vowed to work for a better world environment. It was, in the words
of one official involved in the two-year preparations for that single
moment, 'inspirational'.
Mr Nawaz Sharif, the prime minister of Pakistan speaking on behalf of the
developing countries, said simply: 'After this summit the world will never
be the same again.' Mr Erskine Sandiford, the prime minister of Barbados was
so moved that he penned an ode to the environment.
But to the rest of the world, subjected for 12 days to the massive coverage
provided by the 9,000-strong press corps, the results must have seemed far
more confusing. What had this grandly-titled conference really been about,
with its curious vocabulary of bio-diversity and sustainable development?
How would it affect their lives? Did it even matter?
In one sense, the Earth Summit was a dismal failure. Billed as the event
that would finally place the environment at the top of the global agenda,
its readily identifiable achievements were disappointingly few. All its
decisions fell well short of the original goals. They also look haphazard:
there are measures to protect forests, the climate and plant and animal
life, but none on water or waste, or even population control which was
widely hailed as the best form of environmental protection. The summit also
spent an enormous amount of time arguing about aid to the Third World, a
subject which, to inhabitants of the industrial world at least, might seem
far removed from everyday environmental concerns.
But in another sense, the Earth Summit was a monumental success. It was the
first convocation of world leaders since the end of the Cold war, and as
such demonstrated the strong pulling power of the environment as a political
issue. The gruelling negotiations, which lasted until dawn on several
nights, may have wearied the participants, but they stirred rigorous debate
on whole areas of policy which had never been examined before. And the sheer
weight of publicity - even of the White House's hapless handling of the
event - created a momentum for environmentalists to harness.
But if the summit achieved so little in hard terms, it was because it showed
just how divisive even the most worthy of environmental goals can be, and
the extent to which they touch upon vital national interests. This was
disheartening for those who hoped for concrete results. But in another sense
it was also very educative.
One of the liveliest topics, for example, was the preservation of tropical
forests. Yet the conference failed to agree on an international conservation
treaty, ending instead with a much watered down 'declaration of principles'
which was immediately denounced by Friends of the Earth, the environmental
lobby group, as a 'chainsaw charter'. The real issue had nothing to do with
trees but with whether the world had a right to tell a country how to manage
its natural resources. The fact that it was mainly the rich countries which
were trying to get the poor countries to give up their logging livelihoods
only made it worse.
Another knotty question arose with a bio-diversity treaty. This was
originally proposed as a measure to preserve plant and animal life. But the
real issue quickly became the exact opposite: how living organisms could be
commercially exploited, and who should have the patent rights. The treaty
that was finally agreed was more about commerce than conservation, which is
one reason why the US refused to sign it even though it originally mooted
the idea. As Mr William Reilly, the administrator of the US Environment
Protection Agency, said: 'We would have hoped that the conference would have
confined itself to protecting flora and fauna.'
The other specific agreement - on climate change - threw up a further set of
difficulties. The purpose of this treaty was to curb emissions of greenhouse
gases which threaten to alter the planet's climate. Instead it turned into a
tussle over how big a sacrifice individual countries should make to support
a global cause, in this case by accepting tough emission controls even at
the cost of economic growth. For President George Bush, there was a clear
limit, and he insisted on weaker emission targets before he would sign.
Underlying all these issues lay an even greater question: how far the
world's environmental problems could be traced to the gap between the rich
north and the poor south. The summit's official title was the UN Conference
on the Environment and Development, a title that was supposed to stress the
closeness of the two themes.
For the Third World, there was no question about this link. Mr Anwar
Saifullah, Pakistan's environment minister, said: 'Eighty per cent of our
water is untreated. That's our biggest problem. When I have to worry about
such basic provisions of life, it's a luxury to talk of environment.' Much
of the world's degradation - over-exploitation of land, polluted water and
deforestation - can be traced to poverty, and the voracious demands of the
industrial countries, now and in colonial times.
The Group of 77 developing countries came to Rio determined to secure a
strong increase in aid as the price of their support for the conference. But
though their case was strongly argued, and supported by the World Bank among
others, the Third World did not win the day.
The rich countries acknowledged that they placed the heaviest strains on
world resources and bore a special responsibility to repair the damage. They
also agreed in principle to provide 'new and additional financial means' to
boost environmental aid for the Third World. But when it came to putting
actual money on the table, they were tight-fisted, citing recession and
other budgetary pressures. The financial pledges made in Rio were so vague
that it is hard to size them up. But they appear to amount to Dollars 2.5bn
a year. This is well below the Dollars 5bn-Dollars 10bn that had been
predicted, and mere chicken feed beside the Dollars 70bn which the UN said
was needed. To the bitter end, many rich countries resisted pressure to
commit themselves to raising their aid to the UN target of 0.7 per cent of
gross national product by the turn of the century.
But if the summit must be judged a failure for those who sought to link
poverty to the environment, it achieved a success of a different sort. All
the rich industrial countries committed themselves to giving more aid
specifically for environmental projects, such as sewage treatment, waste
management and cleaner air. Strong support was also given to the Global
Environment Facility, a fund administered by the World Bank and the UN
specifically to help poor countries carry out work which is of value to the
planet as a whole. Environment has thus moved higher up the aid agenda.
The summit also witnessed a shift of a different sort, in the relative roles
of the US and Japan. Washington's aversion to environmental over-regulation,
to the moral obligations included in the summit's legally binding treaties,
and to the attacks that were made on the US appetite for energy and
resources made Mr Bush a reluctant and prickly participant. 'Environment
protection has replaced communism as the great threat to capitalism,' said
one member of the faction-riven US delegation.
By contrast, Japan approached Rio with a carefully planned diplomatic
offensive backed by the largest offer of new environmental aid made at the
summit - some Dollars 500m a year. Whatever Tokyo's motives - and sceptics
were quick to hint that these were driven above all by self-interest - Japan
added measurably to its international status in Rio. 'They're the owners of
all the new issues - and they're getting it so cheap,' said a senior
Brazilian official with mixed admiration and regret.
The real question now that Rio is over is whether it will make any
difference. The answer is virtually none in the short term. The measures
that were agreed, and the financial commitments that were made, were so
modest that the critics can convincingly argue that it was a waste of time.
A more profound reason for questioning the summit's value is that it was
supposed to put the world economy on a path to sustainable development -
that is, by growing in a way that does not impoverish future generations.
But though the summit gave ringing endorsements of this concept, it produced
no binding agreements to force governments to promote it. Green lobby groups
were pressing hard for measures to encourage trade in goods that are
produced on a sustainable basis, or to build true environmental costs into
the manufacturing process. But these were all dismissed as unrealistic in
the harsh reality of the economic world.
Mr Charles de Haes, director general of World Wide Fund for Nature, the
green organisation which helped develop the notion of sustainable
development, described the summit results as minimal. He said: 'It's all
generalities. We need to know specifically what is going to be done and by
when.'
Yet it is hard to escape the impression that Rio did set some very large, if
slow-moving, wheels in motion. Two legally binding treaties will now be
implemented, and more may follow. A commission on sustainable development
will be created to monitor implementation of the summit's decisions, and put
pressure on countries to live up to its spirit. And even if Rio did not
provide the answers, it pressed people's noses very hard against the
questions. One hundred and seventy eight governments put themselves on the
environmental hook, and it will be up to their constituents to keep them
there.
President Francois Mitterrand of France, whose stance was among the most
prominent of the industrialised countries, proposed another 'rendezvous' in
three to five years to review progress.
'We know we still have an enormous way to go in narrowing our points of view
so as to produce common solutions,' he said. 'But our meeting will not have
been in vain if it teaches the people of the south that ecology is not a
rich man's luxury, and those of the north that there is no true
environmental protection without help with development.'
WHAT WAS AGREED AT RIO .....
Treaty on climate change to curb emissions of greenhouse gases
Statement of principles on forests: non-binding agreement to conserve
forests
Bio-diversity treaty to preserve flora and fauna.  US refused to sign
because it weakens bio-technology patent rights
Agenda 21: action plan covering all aspects of environment. Non-binding, but
a yardstick against which to measure government actions
  ...AND WHAT WAS NOT
Treaty on forests: dropped because of Third World opposition.  Its failure
was summit's biggest setback.
Earth Charter: its simple precepts were not up to the complexities created
by summit debate
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 16
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-2791</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CFOA5ADQFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920615
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUN 92 / Arts: Samson et Dalila - Opera
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID MURRAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The revival of Saint-Saens' opera at Covent Garden on Saturday was the 143rd
Midland Bank Prom, with 700 eager fans sitting on the floor of the stalls.
Outside in the piazza, there was a still larger crowd watching it on the
giant screen (courtesy of the Royal Opera House Trust, the Covent Garden
Friends, the City of Westminster and Premium Cinzano). With such overflowing
generosity and enthusiasm, all that was needed was good weather and a really
good performance: both of which we got.
This time round, Elijah Moshinsky's 1981 production has been rehearsed to
excellent purpose by Jeremy Sutcliffe. Sidney Nolan's designs, which lend an
Aboriginal tang to the Near East, still look fine. So does Placido Domingo,
the original Samson of the production, though his elegant distress while
pushing the millstone around suggests a fastidious Duke in exile rather than
a legendary strong-man. (Jon Vickers' bull-like frame was always an
unbeatable advantage there.)
By Domingo's own lofty standards he was only in second-best voice - incisive
and eloquent at the millstone in despair, slightly out of puff when the time
came to pull down the temple. There were of course all his usual marks of
thoughtful integrity; and with his new Dalila, he conducted himself with
perfect gallantry. For young Olga Borodina is a new star of the first
magnitude, as the entire house soon recognised; and far from attempting to
pull operatic rank, Domingo played to her as to an equal. The
seduction-scene at the heart of Act 2 was for once a seriously erotic
affair, not an operatic contest.
Miss Borodina is tall and beautiful, and her warm mezzo is a lovely
instrument: ample, not huge, but never forced. Where many another Dalila
vamps strenuously, she sang limpid phrases, the more penetrating because
they were so effortlessly balanced. Her French is secure (rare among Russian
artists nowadays), if not exactly native; and she inhabits her billowing
costumes with languorous grace. The combination of gentle facade with
unbending inner purpose is extraordinarily potent.
In plain, familiar French, what Saint-Saens' opera is about is a discarded
mistress (Dalila, a Philistine) who turns nasty, and the off-and-on
strongman (Samson, a Hebrew) who swings helplessly between wanting her and
wanting to follow his God-given instructions to annihilate her tribe. Beyond
the text, however, there are ambiguities of feeling which would normally
seem beyond Saint-Saens' tidy artistic range. Borodina's performance was
positively radioactive with them, and to the end they remained fascinatingly
unresolved.
The rest of the cast are mostly old regulars: Jonathan Summers' stylised
brute of a High Priest, Roderick Earle's sneering Abimelech, Mark Beesley's
staunch Ancient Hebrew. The dancers again fling themselves into David
Bintley's Bacchanale with a will.
That still turns the final scene into a flashy charade - which is no more
than this curiously jerry-built opera deserves; but I want to enter another
plea for some British opera company to get Steven Pimlott to re-stage
Samson. His memorable Bregenz Festival version, with its echoes of the
Holocaust, lent the piece unprecedented force and depth.
For the first time here Mark Ermler conducts the opera, and he finds
consistent musical dignity in a score that contains not a few passages of
ricky-tick and fustian and academic note-spinning. That is a creditable
achievement, and an important strength of this performance. On the last
night, by the way, Domingo's place will be taken by Vladimir Popov.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 15
</PAGE>
