<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUN 92 / Arts: Italian Songbook - Symphony Hall
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW CLEMENTS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
To refugees from London's musical life, concerts in Symphony Hall often have
a familiar look. The programmes of the City of Birmingham Symphony Orchestra
may be a shining exception, but much of what is programmed in Birmingham
crops up around the same time in the capital - the Pittsburgh Symphony
played two concerts there last week before coming south, Richter visited
with one of his London programmes, James Galway and the Philharmonia will
introduce Dave Heath's flute concerto in Birmingham just before its London
premiere.
Some duplication of that kind is inevitable, the economic logic of
concert-giving being as it is. But currently there appears to be more of it
than ever, just when in its second year of active life Symphony Hall needs
to begin carving out an individual artistic profile.
On Wednesday, however, Symphony Hall came up with a celebrity recital all of
its own: Felicity Lott, Thomas Allen and Geoffrey Parsons gave Wolf's
Italian Songbook to a sizeable and immensely appreciative audience. Not a
full house, but a very decent one, demonstrating that although the public
for recitals may not yet be as large in Birmingham as it is for orchestral
concerts (which it isn't in London either), it is building all the time.
Lott's and Allen's performances were beautifully wrought; Parsons'
accompaniments began in a slightly unfocused way and gained steadily in
point and purpose. It took all the performers, in fact, the first group of
songs to settle down and to judge the hall exactly. There was a surprising
amount of resonance around the voices, and a consequent emotional distancing
until the ear adjusted, and then the two singers' arts seemed exactly
complementary.
Lott produced some deliciously silvery tones and elegant phrasing - a
beautiful sense of shape in 'Wir haben beide' - and kept the coquettish side
under strict control; Allen was at his best in the more ebullient songs,
sometimes seeming a little laboured when required to sustain a line,
especially in the lowest register. Yet such passing moments of uncertainty
were invariably followed by a number delivered with perfect judgement; so,
after a distinctly uncomfortable 'Heut Nacht erhob ich mich', there was
immediately a beautifully proportioned 'Schon streckt' ich aus'. Sense of
proportion was the essence of everything about the evening; nothing was out
of scale or place, nothing was contrived for cheap effect.
Symphony Hall, Birmingham
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
